<h1>Tutorial 40. Making Ribbon Loops for the Lacing.</h1>
<p><strong>Here is how ribbon loops will be positioned on the waistband: </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image002.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>Let me explain how to determine their correct positioning. </strong></p>
<p><strong>I take a piece of squared paper and draw a vertical line in the middle of it (1).</strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image004.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>I mark the length of the bone which goes along the lacing edge.</strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image006.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image008.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>I mark the area where the ribbon loops are supposed to be made. </strong>They must not arrive at the very end of the bone so I leave some space above and below it. <strong>I measure the resulting area. It is 9cm long. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image010.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>Next, I draw another vertical line 1cm from the first line. </strong>The back ends of the lacing loops are not supposed to go beyond this line (2). The area between lines (1) and (2) will be overlaid by the lacing-edge bone with a width of 1.2cm.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image012.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>My loops will be 7mm long when not pulled on. I draw a third vertical line 7mm from line (1) to mark the top border of the loops. </strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image014.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong>Then I start marking the loops themselves. </strong>It is enough to make them 1.5cm wide. For this purpose, I divide the corresponding section of line (1) <strong>in 1.5cm sections.</strong> As the result, there will be six loops along either lacing edge of the waistband. I number the start and end points of the loops from 1 to 7 (see below).</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image016.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>I mark the top points of the loops along the third line opposite to the midpoints of the sections marked along the first line. </strong>The intervals between these new points marked along line (3) are 1.5cm. I number the top points of the loops from 1 to 6.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image018.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>Then I mark points along line (2) opposite to the points I have just marked along line (3). </strong>These points show where one loop stops and the next one begins. They are also numbered from 1 to 6.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image020.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>I have shown you how to position the loops and now I can start making them. </strong>I will work with a pencil-made layout because it is more precise.</p>
<p><strong>I cover the paper with a piece of packaging film and secure it with pins. </strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image022.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong>The loops will be made from 3mm ribbon. </strong>You could also use cord, trimming, or soutache lace.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image024.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>The bottom loop will come from under the lacing-edge bone. </strong>I put the ribbon to point 1 marked on line (1) and position it perpendicular to this line. Its end must go past line (3).</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image026.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>I pin the ribbon down in point 1 marked on line (1). </strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image028.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong>I insert a pin vertically in point 1 marked on line (3) and wrap the ribbon around it. </strong>Try to wrap the ribbon around the pin very evenly to avoid distortion.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image030.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>I pin the ribbon down in point 2 marked on line (1). Here is the first loop. </strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image032.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong>I move the ribbon horizontally under the supposed bone which will secure the loops and pin it down near line (1) between points 1 and 2. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image034.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>I turn the ribbon toward the top point of the loop making sure it doesn’t get twisted, and pin it down in point 2 marked on line (1) near the end of the first loop.</strong> I have therefore pinned down the beginning of the second loop coming from under the lacing-edge bone.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image036.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>I insert a pin vertically in point 2 on line (3) and wrap the ribbon around it. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image038.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>Then, I secure the ribbon with a pin in point 3 marked along line (1). The second loop is ready. I pin the ribbon down near line (2) between points 2 and 3. </strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image040.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong>I make a turn toward the top point of the loop and pin the ribbon down in point 3 on line (1) near the end of the second loop.</strong> I have thereby secured the beginning of the third loop coming from under the lacing-edge bone. <strong>I insert a pin vertically in point 3 marked along line (3) and wrap the ribbon around it. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image042.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>I pin the ribbon down in point 4 marked on line (1). The third loop is ready now. I pin the ribbon down near line (2) between points 3 and 4. Then, I make a turn toward the top point of the loop and secure the ribbon with a pin in point 4 marked on line (1), near the end of the third loop. </strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image044.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong>All six loops are formed in the same technique. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image046.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image048.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image050.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>I have formed all loops along the first lacing edge of the waistband. </strong>I trim the excess ribbon.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image052.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>I remove the pins along line (2).</strong> The loops pass onto the area which will be covered by the bone and stay within its borders. At the same time, it is very important that the ribbon does not get interrupted.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image054.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>I take a tube of Gütermann glue and smear the loop tops in the area which will be covered by the bone </strong>to make them adhere to the bone itself.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image056.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image058.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image060.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>The fabric-encased bone also needs to be smeared with glue. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image062.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>I position the bone correctly with regard to the loops and press it down firmly. </strong>Then I leave it for about 10 minutes to let the glue set properly.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image064.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>After the glue sets, I remove the pins, lift the packaging film, and carefully take off the lacing panel.</strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image066.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image068.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image070.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>I trim the ends of the ribbon. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image072.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>The lacing panel is ready. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image074.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>I made the second lacing panel while I was waiting for the glue to set on the first one. </strong></p>
<p><strong>Both lacing panels are ready.</strong> There are neat symmetric ribbon loops on them. It did not take any complicated preparations or techniques to make these loops. I believe everything was clear and you now know how to add ribbon loops to a garment.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image075.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image077.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>I sew the lacing panels to the waistband. </strong>I align the panel with the line marked on the central back piece and secure it with two parallel rows of stitches made along the edges of the bone.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image079.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image081.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image083.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image085.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>I sew the other panel on the waistband. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image087.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image089.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image091.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>I trim the ends of the fabric casing to make them level with the edge of the waistband. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image093.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>The lacing edges look perfectly symmetric. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image094.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>When I fold the seam allowance, there will be enough space between the loops along the opposite lacing edges, and the lacing will look more pronounced. </strong>You can also put hard bones along the lacing edges.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image096.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>The face part of the waistband is also ready and now I can join it with the lining. </strong></p>
<p><strong>I pin the face to the lining along the two vertical edges and along the top edge inserting pins in a gliding motion.</strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image098.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image100.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>I sew over the side of the lining right along the row of stay-stitches.</strong> I make bar tacks at the beginning and at the end of each row of stitches and I don’t turn the garment on the needle.</p>
<p><strong>I join the pieces along the vertical edges only down to the row of stay-stitches made along the bottom edge of the waistband. It will be easy to sew the waistband to the skirt this way. </strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image102.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong>I join the lining with the face along the three sides leaving the bottom edge open. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image104.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image106.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image108.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image110.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image112.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image114.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image116.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>I trim the seam allowances down to 5mm. I trim their ends at an angle at the top and leave them as is below the bottom row of stay-stitches for joining it with the skirt. </strong>I can always notch out the excess fabric later if necessary.</p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image118.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image120.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image122.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image124.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image126.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong>I trim the ends of the princess seam and side seam allowances at an angle. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image128.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>And I turn out the waistband. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image130.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>The corners of the waistband will never be too sharp because of the thickness. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image132.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>The waistband looks great and the vertical bones don’t poke out anywhere. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image134.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>I need to make a tunnel for a hard bone along either lacing edge. If I do this now though, I won’t be able to fold the seam allowance when joining the waistband with the skirt. </strong>For this reason, I will sew the tunnels after sewing the waistband to the skirt.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image136.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>And now I will sew a row of stay-stitches 1cm above the bottom edge of the face of the waistband to fold and press the seam allowance along it. </strong>I will have to jump over the vertical bones to keep open tunnels for inserting hard bones. I should have made this row of stay-stitches before sewing the vertical bones on the waistband but what is done is done.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image138.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image140.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image142.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image144.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image146.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image148.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>After making this row of stay-stitches, I carefully fold the seam allowance along it, press it, and then sew the face of the waistband to the skirt with a lapped seam. </strong>&nbsp;Then, I will sew the lining of the waistband to the skirt along the same line and press the top edge of the waistband.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image150.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2040.files/image152.jpg" alt=""></p>

